title: For Sale:  Early (1922) Remington Model 24 Takedown 'Gallery Gun'/ .22 Short
location: Out Yukon Way, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent:
Here is a 1st 'official' year, (made in 1922), Remington Model 24.
 Technically; about 100 of these were produced by Remington Arms between 1919-21, but 1922 was the Remy Model 24's big debut. This is basically the same gun as the Browning SA-22 that was made in Belgium by Fabrique Nationale (FN) until the 1970's & is still produced in Japan for Browning today, (Note: Late models may be slightly radioactive)- & parts (for the 'most part') interchange.
  These little take-down, take anywhere guns were designed by the Master himself- John Moses Browning. As we all know; JMB  held patent to most of Winchesters best lever guns, & pistols from the ubiquitous Model 1911 to tiny pocket pistols, plus plenty of fire belching machine guns to boot. To this day; It's still considered impolite to hold even a small battle without at least few Browning patents being involved.
  This was one of the most elegant, graceful, & handiest long guns ever created, (they really don't seem 'long' at all). Most Model 24s were chambered in .22 long rifle, but a few were made in .22 short, for the recoil & noise sensitive. 
 Actually; the .22 short versions were known as 'Gallery Guns'- & many were employed at shooting galleries from seaside attractions like Atlantic City, to traveling carnivals, & county fairs across America. For many decades, (back in pre-liberal times when kids actually learned to shoot in the school gym)- before chewed up Pop-Tarts & pointed fingers became 'dangerous weapons', & 'zero tolerance' reigned supreme- the Model 24 was 'Queen of the Midway'.
 Most of these little gal's were rode hard & put away damp. This one is no exception, but at 92 years of age she's earned her 'patina' by golly! If this gun could only talk, it might groan a little, but I bet it has some amazing tales to tell. Like how she lost a piece of her Schnabel forearm and had to have another piece of walnut grafted in from a kindly donor Remington, or how every time she was dragged to another engagement miles away, a little more of her factory bluing stayed behind, until finally she just decided to 'go with it' and became proud of her road-weary looks, dammit!
Like Keith Richards' Telecaster...(or old Kieth Himself, for that matter).
 This little gun still loves to go out plinking & have fun, but reserves the right to be slightly cantankerous at times. I did run some 'high velocity' (yeah, right) .22 short thru her & she ran flawlessly...so maybe she's just a tad 'ammo sensitive' like most .22 autos.
It would also look great hanging on the wall & will give your lair an aura of mystery & danger- particularly if you tell all yer friends that ,"Yup- this here was John Dillinger's favorite squirrel rifle". It really does have a lot of History behind it, especially for a 'Civilian' gun.
 I picked it up in the Wild West- and it looked right at home there too. In fact; it very well  may have just been there all along....but that's another story. 
Don't let my humble description scare you away, it's still a very solid (& elegant!) little rifle, and as early a Model 24 as you are likely to find. I'm asking $250 in increasingly worthless Fed Notes or might just trade for a High Standard Sentinel .22 revolver....unless you have a better idea..... Silver?

title: For Sale:  Beretta 96D w/ both .40 and 9mm barrels, mags, holsters and more!
postcontent:
I have for sale a used but in good condition police trade in Beretta 96D. A single action sear and hammer have been added in order to obtain traditional DA/SA functionality. This modification allows this originally DAO model to function similarly to a 96F DA/SA gun, minus the safety decocker (the original bobbed DAO hammer is included in this package.) 

Mechanically the function is flawless. Since I have owned it I have shot no less than 500 rounds through it without a single malfunction. No visible cracks can be found on the slide or locking block. Being that this was originally a DAO gun, the trigger pull is much more pleasant in double action than on a 96F or 92FS. This package also includes a 9MM conversion barrel which has been used on a couple of occasions also without malfunction. 

Cosmetically the gun is in decent condition. It was a duty gun before I bought it and had a lot of holster wear, scratches and dings. It has since been refinished with a very durable epoxy based paint, but there are some visible dings and scratches in the metal beneath the new finish. It was originally equipped with Trijicon night sights, but they went too dim to use, so I had the lamps removed from the sights in preparation to have fresh ones installed. I never got around to it, so the sights simply have three holes drilled through them waiting to receive either some new tritium lamps or some fiber-optic dots. 

Included in the package are as follows.


The original DAO hammer.
The original pair of rubber grips.
A 9mm conversion Barrel.
One .40S&W 11 round factory magazine.
Two CheckMate M9 9MM 15 round GI magazines.
One Remora IWB holster with high sweat shield.
One Safariland ALS OWB Level II retention holster (The best holster I've ever used) w/ paddle and belt loop mounting hardware.
One Blackhawk CQC non retention OWB holster w/ paddle and belt loop mounting hardware.


For this complete Beretta package, equipped with everything you need to start shooting and carrying either .40S&W or 9mm, I am asking $425. 

I am willing to hear offers, but I feel as though this package is offering a whole lot of value at that price for a really fine shooter. Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Original Marlin Model 1895 .45-70 NOT A REMINGTON
location: Santa Fe, Nm, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
I bought this rifle a couple of months ago from a local ATF agent (a very good guy actually) based in Albuquerque. He had picked it up because his nephew had drawn for a buffalo "hunt"  here. He sighted the rifle in, and his nephew shot the buffalo. Then he put the rifle in his safe, and there it sat until I got it from him.

 When I got it, I zeroed it with the factory sights, and some regular 400 grain factory Remington ammo. Then installed the Williams peep sight, and did the same thing. Then I also put it in my safe. Total rounds fired were 20, and in the foreseeable future that is about it as well. So I see no need to keep it when someone else might enjoy it more.

 Now to the rifle itself. This appears to be an early 1990s Model 1895. It is still a Marlin with a nice walnut stock and finish, not one of the half-finished fencepost died-hardwood stocks that Remington is putting on them nowadays. The action is smooth as silk and there is no rust, pitting, etc. The rifle was very accurate when sighted in, and I shot cloverleaf groups with it at 100 yards with the peep sight installed. It looks almost new. There are a couple of very, very, VERY light handling marks on it. The Williams sight is on it and works great, but you can take it off if you don't want to use it. I will include the original filler screws of course. If you want, The screw-in fine sight aperture is also included, but I used it as a ghost ring so it isn't in the picture. The front sight hood is also included. I took it off when I installed the Williams.

Another 'extra" is also on it. You may notice that the silly crossbolt safety isn't on this rifle. That is because it has had the conversion done by a local custom gunsmith who used to make these kits. The bluing on it is perfectly matched, and it just looks like an action screw right now. This is completely reversible, and I will include the original safety as well. Just unscrew the filler, pull it out, and then reinstall the safety as normal. Marlin and Winchester made lever actions for a hundred years without them, so I still don't quite understand why they had to change, except for fear of lawyers. This type of conversion is unobtrusive, and frankly I had to look twice even after the seller showed me to notice it was not original to the rifle. It's one of my favorite features on it. And again, it is reversible in about 30 seconds with a flat screwdriver.

The trigger and action are extremely smooth, and it feeds perfectly. There are NO issues wth this rifle that need to be explained away. it is made the way they used to be made, and not the cheap way they do now. the .45-70 in normal factory loads is very mild, but still with great killing power. this one killed a buffalo after all. but the recoil on it is much less than a .30-30. if you want, the action on the 1895 is strong enough to take some very heavy loads indeed, and that is why they are so popular in Alaska for bears. 

I have had no problem buying ammo for it, and places like Sportsmans Warehouse and Ron Petersons have it in stock.

Contact me through Armslist with your phone number and I'll give you a call to set up a time to see it. You will not be disappointed.. This rifle can be shipped within this state to New Mexico residents  without using an FFL. If you are too far away  to drive up and see it. shipping would be $25 if you choose that option.
